Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Alonzo Lee Williams in court with attorney Kevin Brian Dunn.  Jessica Bellows appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy Court Clerk: KAR.
Case calendared for status conference.  State advised the Court they have complied with the Victims' Rights Law.  Negotiations placed on the record by the state.

AS TO COUNT 1: Defendant changes plea to GUILTY. Defendant examined as to his plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty. Court found that defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights. Plea questionnaire, addendum and jury instructions received and filed. Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea. Court found defendant guilty as charged in the criminal complaint and ordered a judgment of conviction be entered on the record. Defendant further advised that if he is not a US citizen deportation is possible.

Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant.
Defendant sentenced to serve 6 MONTHS in the House of Correction, consecutive to any other sentence, with credit for 41 days time served.  COURT STAYED THE SENTENCE and placed the defendant on probation with the State of Wisconsin, Department of Corrections for a period of 18 months.

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION:
* Mental Health Evaluation and take ALL prescribed medication and/or any treatment deemed appropriate.          
* Successfully complete Anger Management.
* Defendant to participate in Alcohol and Drug Assessment and successfully complete recommended treatment including random urine screens.
* Maintain absolute sobriety.  Defendant NOT to possess or use any controlled substances unless by valid prescription.
* Successfully complete any other counseling and/or treatment deemed appropriate.
* No contact with victim, Brittany W.  Warning given.
* Pay all mandatory costs, fees and surcharges during the period of probation, cash bail to apply.  Any remaining balance at the end of probation will be due immediately or entry of a civil judgment.
* Pay all supervision fees.
* Obtain and maintain full-time employment, school, or combination of both.
* Obtain GED or HSED.
* Successfully complete 12 hours of community service with a non-profit organization.
* No firearms; weapons.
* Defendant to submit a DNA sample and pay the DNA surcharge.
* Restitution is set at $0.
